 from a resource with predefined settings. However, there's a rule advising against creating tests for behavior that relies on runtime bytecode generation, class definition, or loading. It's an interesting limitation, and I wonder how it affects testing practices in those environments.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Inspecting SnappyInputStream**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking into the SnappyInputStream tests and I see there’s no active loader. It seems like I need to focus on behavioral richness, but maybe I'm overcomplicating that. Reducing complexity could help. I should also check out the stream constructors to pinpoint any issues, like whether there's a timeout involved. It’s a lot to juggle! I'll keep examining the details for clarity.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating testing strategies**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering the use of JUnit nested tests with one top-level file. I can't fork per method unless Gradle maxParallel is adjusted, which feels tricky. But I wonder if dynamic-access coverage could aggregate in a child process if the agent is inherited via JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS. Typically, agent options are passed to the test JVM, not the child. So, I can’t rely on that. Maybe using `SnappyLoader` through a public API is a potential option?\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_qiHbOiTMn5xS0bciWUqqkntf|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6a659db88193be035589333ca1a6\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"/home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.xerial.snappy/snappy-java/1.0.4.1/main/extracted/org/xerial/snappy/SnappyInputStream.java\", \"limit\": 120}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 10446, \"output\": 2082, \"cacheRead\": 16896, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 29424, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1782409781609, \"responseId\": \"resp_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6a36698c8193975eb6e0988f033e\"}}\n1782:[tool-exec] start id=call_qiHbOiTMn5xS0bciWUqqkntf|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6a659db88193be035589333ca1a6 name=read args={\"path\": \"/home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.xerial.snappy/snappy-java/1.0.4.1/main/extracted/org/xerial/snappy/SnappyInputStream.java\", \"limit\": 120}\n1908:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating Native Image support**\\n\\nI'm considering how Native Image can support predefined classes if the bytecode is examined during the build. It seems like runtime class definitions could come from a resource with predefined settings. However, there's a rule advising against creating tests for behavior that relies on runtime bytecode generation, class definition, or loading. It's an interesting limitation, and I wonder how it affects testing practices in those environments.\\n\\n**Inspecting SnappyInputStream**\\n\\nI’m looking into the SnappyInputStream tests and I see there’s no active loader. It seems like I need to focus on behavioral richness, but maybe I'm overcomplicating that. Reducing complexity could help. I should also check out the stream constructors to pinpoint any issues, like whether there's a timeout involved. It’s a lot to juggle! I'll keep examining the details for clarity.\\n\\n**Evaluating testing strategies**\\n\\nI’m considering the use of JUnit nested tests with one top-level file. I can't fork per method unless Gradle maxParallel is adjusted, which feels tricky. But I wonder if dynamic-access coverage could aggregate in a child process if the agent is inherited via JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS. Typically, agent options are passed to the test JVM, not the child. So, I can’t rely on that. Maybe using `SnappyLoader` through a public API is a potential option?\", 