I need to look into whether \\\\\\\"forkEvery\\\\\\\" can be configured for test tasks. It feels tricky since it may relate to how JUnit organizes tests in classes. We really want to ensure we're covering supported behavior without asserting known failures, right?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring Snappy Error Handling**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about how to cover scenarios where known failures shouldn't be asserted. If we consider the native image and coverage requirements, I wonder if I could catch a SnappyError when the system library is missing. It gets tricky, though, because the Static implementation might be null while the class initializes. If I adjust the settings to disable bundled libraries and use a real system library, I might navigate around the package-private access issue. I need to ensure all necessary paths are covered effectively!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering SnappyLoader Implementation**\\\\n\\\\nI’m wondering if setting \\\\\\\"useSystemLib=false\\\\\\\" after the system library branch could help, allowing SnappyLoader.load to recognize the API already in place, which would skip line 383. It feels complicated since bundling first and then switching to system libraries seems impossible due to API constraints. I could explore using reflection to \\\\\\\"unload\\\\\\\" components, but that might be restricted unless it's a public API. Keeping everything efficient could involve using a separate JVM within the Gradle test while ensuring the dynamic agent connects properly.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_bdGMYQJYFXR9DEGP1KXMUwFZ|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6c975c2c8193b65c6a60ed061184\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"dynamic-access|javaagent|forkEvery|agentlib:native-image-agent|JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS\\\" tests -n | head -200\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1360