819392278a78c6098d08\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_7966pHPJYdnZSOLbh0OIns0j|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6c9fa0648193b6cc3d6be71c50f8\", \"toolName\": \"read\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage org.graalvm.internal.tck.harness.tasks;\\n\\nimport org.gradle.api.tasks.TaskAction;\\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.stats.LibraryStatsModels;\\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.stats.LibraryStatsSupport;\\n\\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\\nimport java.util.List;\\n\\n/**\\n * Generates a per-class dynamic-access coverage report for matching coordinates.\\n *\\n * <p>The output is written as JSON to\\n * {@code metadata/<group>/<artifact>/<version>/test/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json}\\n * and has this shape:\\n *\\n * <pre>{@code\\n * {\\n *   \\\"coordinate\\\": \\\"group:artifact:version\\\",\\n *   \\\"hasDynamicAccess\\\": true,\\n *   \\\"totals\\\": {\\n *     \\\"totalCalls\\\": 10,\\n *     \\\"coveredCalls\\\": 6\\n *   },\\n *   \\\"classes\\\": [\\n *     {\\n *       \\\"className\\\": \\\"com.example.Foo\\\",\\n *       \\\"sourceFile\\\": \\\"Foo.java\\\",\\n *       \\\"totalCalls\\\": 4,\\n *       \\\"coveredCalls\\\": 2,\\n *       \\\"callSites\\\": [\\n *         {\\n *           \\\"metadataType\\\": \\\"reflection\\\",\\n *           \\\"trackedApi\\\": \\\"java.lang.Class#forName(java.lang.String)\\\",\\n *           \\\"frame\\\": \\\"com.example.Foo.load(Foo.java:10)\\\",\\n *           \\\"line\\\": 10,\\n *           \\\"covered\\\": true\\n *         }\\n *       ]\\n *     }\\n *   ]\\n * }\\n * }</pre>\\n *\\n * <p>The JSON payload is emitted from {@link LibraryStatsModels.DynamicAccessCoverageReport}.\\n *\\n * <p>Implements §TCK-test-harness.8 — the {@code generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport} task.\\n */\\n@SuppressWarnings(\\\"unused\\\")\\npublic abstract class GenerateDynamicAccessCoverageReportTask extends AbstractLibraryStatsTask {\\n\\n    @TaskAction\\n    public void generate() {\\n        List<String> coordinates = resolveRequestedCoordinates();\\n        for (String coordinate : coordinates) {\\n            generateReportsForCoordinate(coordinate);\\n            List<Path> libraryJars = listLibraryJars(coordinate);\\n            LibraryStatsModels.DynamicAccessCoverageReport report = LibraryStatsSupport.buildDynamicAccessCoverageReport(\\n                    coordinate,\\n                    libraryJars,\\n                    getDynamicAccessDir(coordinate),\\n                    getJacocoReport(coordinate)\\n            );\\n            Path outputFile = getDynamicAccessCoverageReport(coordinate);\\n            LibraryStatsSupport.writeJson(outputFile, report);\\n            getLogger().quiet(\\\"Wrote dynamic-access coverage report for {} to {}.\\\", coordinate, outputFile);\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1782410399967}]}\n5108:[thinking] I'm thinking about how the default `test` task and custom `systemLibTest` relate to each other. The dynamic coverage report seems to depend on `nativeTestCompile`, not just `test`. I'm also wondering if the javaTest relates only to the basic test. The Jacoco report includes the test task, so I might need to configure Jacoco for multiple test tasks, but that feels broad. Maybe a simpler approach is to use `tasks.withType(Test).configureEach { forkEvery = 1 }` and create a second test method.\n5112:[thinking] I need to compute the OS and architecture in Gradle. One idea is to copy the resource name from the jar. However, the `java.library.path` needs to be set before running tests. Am I also considering the native image runtime? For the `nativeTest`, using `System.loadLibrary` means I need the `java.library.path` to include the actual external library. I’m also thinking about what resources are necessary for `nativeTest` compilation.\n5118:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Java testing structure**\\n\\nI'm exploring if I can put two public top-level test classes in one Java file, but it looks like that's not possible since only one public class per file is allowed. I wonder if using JUnit `@Nested` classes could help, as they might get executed in the same JVM. However, it seems Gradle may need separate processes.\\n\\nI might configure the Gradle test task to run tests in separate processes, using `forkEvery = 1`. I could also adjust the settings for max parallel forks or use specific JVM arguments. It’s all a bit intricate!\\n\\n**Analyzing coverage issues**\\n\\nI’m considering if the final dynamic coverage will leave line 311 uncovered, which could lead to a failure. The automation might accept incremental adjustments, reporting active coverage based on current files and newly executed tests. However, the tasks seem to ask for tests that ensure all uncovered call sites are reached, rather than just preserving previous coverage. If I switch branches, it’s likely that previously covered line 383 remains uncovered because the code can still cover it during the native image build process. It's a bit of a conundrum!\\n\\n**Considering test configurations**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how the default `test` task and custom `systemLibTest` relate to each other. The dynamic coverage report seems to depend on `nativeTestCompile`, not just `test`. I'm also wondering if the javaTest relates only to the basic test. The Jacoco report includes the test task, so I might need to configure Jacoco for multiple test tasks, but that feels broad. Maybe a simpler approach is to use `tasks.withType(Test).configureEach { forkEvery = 1 }` and create a second test method.\\n\\n**Exploring Gradle Native Config