ion. However, I wonder if the jacocoTestReport depends on the `test` task — could that mean the finalizer runs before jacoco? Since finalized tasks run after the `test` but might impact the order of execution, I need to ensure the dependencies are correctly set up to avoid conflicts. It's a bit tricky, so I want to double-check my approach.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_SPTUeKaU36wY9xcyWhouQ5Z6|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6d0b5ffc8193be578e0f0d59967d\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"javaTest\\\" -n build.gradle settings.gradle tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 469, \"output\": 2320, \"cacheRead\": 56320, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 59109, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1782410460854, \"responseId\": \"resp_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6cddf4a8819396bd1c52d938ee80\"}}\n5623:[tool-exec] start id=call_SPTUeKaU36wY9xcyWhouQ5Z6|fc_0b01435cdb5be1c0016a3d6d0b5ffc8193be578e0f0d59967d name=bash args={\"command\": \"rg \\\"javaTest\\\" -n build.gradle settings.gradle tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy\"}\n5633:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating test configuration**\\n\\nI'm considering modifying the build.gradle file to run two Test tasks, merging jacoco exec into a single `test.exec`. It sounds complex, but it could avoid extra test files. The idea is to have one test class that operates in two modes based on a system property. The `test` task will have a bundled mode, while a new `systemLibraryTest` will run in system mode. I need to ensure the configuration handles dependencies properly too.\\n\\n**Considering task finalization**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using `tasks.named('test') { finalizedBy systemLibra